					xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"
					xmlns:db="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">

	<refnamediv>
		<refname>hamm_encode</refname>

		<refpurpose>Hamming Encoding</refpurpose>
	</refnamediv>

	<refsynopsisdiv>
		<title>Calling Sequence</title>

		<synopsis> a = hamm_encode(b,c)</synopsis>
	</refsynopsisdiv>
	
	<refsection>

		<title>Parameters</title>

		<variablelist>                                                                            
			<varlistentry><term>a:</term>
				<listitem><para> output single dimension binary encoded array of {0,1}.</para></listitem></varlistentry>      
                         <varlistentry><term>b:</term>        
				<listitem><para> input single dimension binary array of {0,1}.</para></listitem></varlistentry>   
			<varlistentry><term>c:</term>        
				<listitem><para> input positive non zero integer.</para></listitem></varlistentry>        
		</variablelist>

	</refsection>



	<refsection>
		<title>Description</title>

		<para>Hamming Encoding. </para>
	
		<para>The function encodes the input bit stream using the Hamming Encoding scheme
		</para>

		<para>It is expected that the user inputs a single dimension binary matrix of (0,1) and an integer m while calling the hamm_encode() function and expect the function to return a single dimension binary matrix of (0,1) as encoded output in scilab console.
		</para>
		
	</refsection>

	<refsection>
		<title>Examples</title>

		<programlisting role="example">b=[0 0 1 1 1 0 1 0];&#10;c=3;&#10;a=hamm_encode(b,c)</programlisting>
	</refsection>

	<refsection>
		<title>Authors</title>

		<simplelist type="vert">
			<member>Aishwarya Tripathi</member>
		</simplelist>
	</refsection>
</refentry>
